    <stitle>VT 275 Engine Service Manual - Rear Cover - Removal - Rear Cover</stitle>
    <svcman/>
    <svcproc id="s26513.1.7" svcproctype="remove" graphiccount="7">
        <title>Rear Cover</title>
        <figure id="f3000114001" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figJ06/J06064.cgm" type="cgm" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"/>
            <caption>Rear cover bolt arrangement (stripped chassis)</caption>
            <calloutgroup>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Bolt, M8 x 55 (5)</callout1>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Bolt, M10 x 60 (4)</callout1>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Bolt, M10 x 70 (2)</callout1>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Crankshaft rear oil seal carrier</callout1>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Bolt, M8 x 25 (6)</callout1>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Bolt, M8 x 70 (2)</callout1>
            </calloutgroup>
        </figure>
        <figure id="f3000114001.5" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figJ06/J06070.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"/>
            <caption>Rear cover bolt arrangement (CF)</caption>
            <calloutgroup>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Bolt, M8 x 35 (8)</callout1>
            </calloutgroup>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Stripped Chassis - Remove necessary rear cover mounting bolts. Refer to for rear cover bolt
                pattern.
            </para>
            <para>CF Chassis - Remove eight rear cover mounting bolts (M8 x 35). Refer to for rear cover bolt pattern.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <specpara>
            <caution>
                <para>To prevent engine damage when removing the rear cover, cut the sealant where the crankcase and
                    lower crankcase meet.
                </para>
                <para>Cut sealant where the crankcase, high-pressure oil pump cover and rear cover meet.</para>
                <para>Failure to adequately cut sealant prior to removing rear cover could result in upper and lower
                    crankcase gaskets being pulled out. Complete engine removal and disassembly would be required to
                    replace the lower crankcase gasket.
                </para>
            </caution>
        </specpara>
        <figure id="e3001409" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figJ06/J06019.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"/>
            <caption>Removing the rear cover with a rubber hammer (typical)</caption>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Use a rubber hammer to help loosen the rear cover from its seat.</para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">When the rear cover becomes loose, pull back on the rear cover but do not remove
                completely.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <specpara>
            <caution>
                <para>To prevent engine damage, (if high-pressure oil pump cover is in place), make sure the
                    high-pressure oil pump cover gasket does not pull out when removing the rear cover.
                </para>
            </caution>
        </specpara>
        <figure id="e3001410" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figJ06/J06020.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"/>
            <caption>Cutting the rear cover gasket (typical)</caption>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Cut the rear cover gasket from under the high-pressure pump housing in order to remove the
                rear cover. Pull the rear cover back, but do not remove.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="e3001411" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figJ06/J06021.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"/>
            <caption>Separating the rear cover from the lower crankcase gasket (typical)</caption>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Use a thin gasket scraper to separate sealant between the upper and lower crankcase seals
                and rear cover assembly. When removing the rear cover assembly, separate the sealant at all joints with
                the rear cover to avoid pulling these gaskets out.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="e3001412" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figJ06/J06025.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px" box="no"/>
            <caption>Removing the rear cover assembly (CF)</caption>
            <calloutgroup>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Alignment dowels</callout1>
            </calloutgroup>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the rear cover assembly.</para>
        </step1>
        <specpara>
            <warning>
                <para>(Stripped chassis applications only) - To avoid serious personal injury or possible death, have an
                    assistant help with the removal of the rear cover as it is considerably heavier than the CF chassis
                    version. See
                    <hotlnk xrefid="safety">"Safety Information</hotlnk>."
                </para>
            </warning>
        </specpara>
        <figure id="e3001413" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figJ06/J06043.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"/>
            <caption>Removing the rear cover gasket (typical)</caption>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the rear cover gasket and discard.</para>
        </step1>
